    "statement": "You are given an array of integers **sorted in ascending order** and a target value. Return the 1-indexed positions of the two numbers that add up exactly to the target, as a two-element array `[i, j]` with `i < j`. You may assume exactly one valid pair exists, and you may not use the same element twice.\n\nYour solution should run in O(n) time using the two-pointer technique — an O(n^2) brute force will time out on the hidden tests.",
    "examples": [
      {
        "input": "nums = [2, 7, 11, 15], target = 9",
        "output": "[1, 2]",
        "explanation": "nums[0] + nums[1] = 2 + 7 = 9, so the 1-indexed positions are 1 and 2."
      },
      {
        "input": "nums = [1, 2, 3], target = 5",
        "output": "[2, 3]",
        "explanation": "nums[1] + nums[2] = 2 + 3 = 5."
      }
    ],
    "starterCode": "public int[] pairSumIndices(int[] nums, int target) {\n    // nums is sorted ascending; return 1-indexed [i, j], i < j\n    // your code here\n    return new int[0];\n}\n",
